	<article class="post-248810 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-budgets-and-budgeting tag-house-of-representatives tag-law-and-legislation tag-midterm-elections-2014 tag-ryan-paul-d-jr tag-united-states-politics-and-government per-ryan-paul-d-jr des-budgets-and-budgeting des-law-and-legislation des-midterm-elections-2014 des-united-states-politics-and-government org-house-of-representatives news_keywords-2014-midterm-elections news_keywords-budget-2 news_keywords-house-of-representatives news_keywords-legislation-2 news_keywords-paul-d-ryan-jr news_keywords-us-politics" id="post-248810">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">10 Questions for Paul Ryan</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By John Harwood			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-31T20:10:43+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 31, 2014 4:10 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 31, 2014 4:10 pm</span>		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w480"><!--<media id="100000003032278" type="video" auto_play="false">--></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Representative Paul D. Ryan of Wisconsin gained a national profile &#8212; and a spot on the 2012 Republican presidential ticket &#8212; by taking an aggressive approach to budget-cutting. But now the House Budget Committee chairman is aiming to broaden his appeal, as well as that of his party.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He struck a budget compromise months ago with his Democratic Senate counterpart, Patty Murray of Washington, and last week unveiled an antipoverty proposal that didn&#8217;t seek a dime of budget savings. Instead, Mr. Ryan proposed consolidating an array of federal programs for the poor in a single funding stream states could accept while tailoring their own approach to providing services.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ryan sat down with The Times&#8217;s John Harwood to discuss his proposal, the performance of Congress and his political future. What follows is a condensed, edited transcript of their conversation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-248810"></span></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Your program for cutting antipoverty initiatives does not cut funding for those programs, it consolidates them.  Is that a signal that you think that Republicans have reached the end of the road in terms of cutting discretionary spending of that kind?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I didn&#8217;t want to get into a debate about proper funding levels of the status quo because we would spend all this time talking about budget numbers. I wanted to start a debate about how to reform the status quo.  The fact of the matter is these reforms could occur at any spending level. You can decide later on.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let&#8217;s take whatever our federal government does in these programs and keep the same level of funding for the states who choose to use the opportunity grant. Let&#8217;s focus our poverty-fighting efforts, not on inputs, not on efforts like how much money we spend, how many programs we create, but are we getting people out of poverty.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Two objections. I <a href="//thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/24/10-questions-for-hillary-rodham-clinton/">talked to Hillary Clinton last week</a> and she said this is not a good idea because if governors won&#8217;t take federal money &#8212; free money &#8212; to expand Medicaid, they can&#8217;t be trusted to protect these programs. And that you eliminate the automatic stabilizers function of these programs that allow them to expand when the economy is worse.</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I&#8217;ll take the last one first. The baseline of funding changes per the economy.  And I would anticipate doing the same thing here with what you call automatic stabilizers. The first point though I just disagree with. This isn&#8217;t free money. States are getting put on the hook with Obamacare,  and then the federal government ratchets down its matching rate. So it is an unfunded mandate at the end of the day.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But more important, it&#8217;s sort of an apples to oranges comparison. It&#8217;s not the same thing for a governor to say, &#8220;I don&#8217;t want to take this top-down, heavy-handed approach from Washington of a government health care system.&#8221;  There&#8217;s nothing inconsistent with the governor saying no to that and then saying yes to, &#8220;I want more flexibility for how to customize &#8212; benefits that get people from welfare to work.&#8221;  So I just don&#8217;t see that as an accurate comparison.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> One of the reasons why Democrats have been hostile to your ideas is that they&#8217;ve taken some of your public comments to mean you think government help is the problem for the poor &#8212; the &#8220;hammock&#8221; is the problem and that the way to help people is actually to take away government assistance.</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> No, I think the hammock&#8217;s the wrong analogy. That&#8217;s wrong. What I worry about are government programs that actually disincentivize work.  And in many cases, and I flesh this out in my report, a person can be worse off leaving government benefits because they lose a lot of money going to work. We need to fix that. We need to remove the disincentive to work and make it so that work always pays.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And so yes, I think the government has been very counterproductive if the goal is to move a person from welfare to work. Number two, I think the federal government inadvertently has displaced a lot of good work at the local level. The government should respect its limits and man the supply lines, not be the front lines. We shouldn&#8217;t work against local poverty fighters, we should work with them.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let&#8217;s have a results-oriented approach where we measure and test results of new, innovative ideas that are being done at the state level so that we can find out what works, so that we can scale that up.  Because what we&#8217;re doing right now in the status quo, it&#8217;s not working.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> There was a lot of doomsday rhetoric early in the Obama administration from Republicans &#8212; we&#8217;re going to be Greece, the president&#8217;s proposals are out of control. You said at one point, &#8220;we&#8217;re living in an Ayn Rand novel&#8221; and that his policies were an attack on the moral foundations of capitalism. Now that unemployment is down, G.D.P. grew 4 percent this quarter, are you willing to say some of that was overheated and hyped up?  Do you really believe President Obama was attacking the moral foundations of the country?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Oh I don&#8217;t &#8212; that&#8217;s a pretty broad statement. Ask me what policy you&#8217;re talking about, then I&#8217;ll give you a reaction. But I think his economic doctrine is the wrong way for the country. I think we could&#8217;ve done far better for economic growth. This is the worst recovery we&#8217;ve had on record.  And I would argue this is the worst recovery we&#8217;ve had since World War II because of the president&#8217;s policies &#8212; because of government policies, regulations, bad energy policy, no willingness to do tax reform, borrowing and spending, not getting the debt under control, loose money from the federal reserve.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Some people would say the way Congress is functioning or not functioning is itself an attack on the moral foundations of the country. What report card do you give Congress, including the Republican House, as you prepare to leave for vacation?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The number I saw yesterday was 351 bills have passed the House of Representatives, aimed at making people&#8217;s lives better, at fixing the problems that are plaguing our government. Forty of the bills are for job creation. All of which are sitting in the United States Senate, gathering dust, going nowhere. Harry Reid has shut down the United States Senate.  They&#8217;re not legislating. And therefore, we have paralyzed government.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If you take a look at what the House has done, our job-creating bills, all the bills we&#8217;ve passed have balanced the budget and paid down the debt. That&#8217;s constructive. But if you only have the House legislating and enacting, not the Senate, then nothing gets done. So I think you can&#8217;t just say all of Congress.  I think you&#8217;ve got to give credit where credit is due. And those of us in Congress who believe in fixing problems with certain solutions have passed those solutions here in the House.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Why haven&#8217;t Republicans in the House passed entitlement reform, the kinds of things you&#8217;ve proposed in your budget? Isn&#8217;t the actual reason that even though you&#8217;re willing to do it, your colleagues are not?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> No, I don&#8217;t think that&#8217;s it. I think we know that the Senate won&#8217;t act on these things.  And we&#8217;re trying to pass a lot of bills that we think have a chance, a reasonable chance of passing into law to make a difference in people&#8217;s lives.  And that&#8217;s why we&#8217;ve been passing things like Keystone pipeline, energy legislation, a job-training legislation.  We would like to think that these things could possibly get a fair hearing in the Senate.  But even those reasonable measures haven&#8217;t gotten a fair hand.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If we had willing partners on the other side of the aisle, if we had a president who was actually willing to tackle our tough fiscal issues, our members in the House would be more than willing to participate in that. But it&#8217;s been abundantly clear to us the Senate and the White House are not interesting in tackling the really big problems facing our country fiscally.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> If Republicans take the Senate, what changes the next two years &#8212; anything?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I think we can actually get Congress working again. We can put a lot of things on the president&#8217;s desk. Harry Reid has been preventing the president from having to make any difficult decisions on any issue because he&#8217;s stopped legislation in the Senate. We would actually have the ability of passing legislation all the way through Congress, not just half the way through, and giving the president the opportunity to make a decision.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But shouldn&#8217;t the conclusion that average Americans reach be that really nothing that&#8217;s going to happen until there&#8217;s a new president?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I hate to think like that. Unfortunately, I think there&#8217;s some merit to that criticism.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I <a href="//thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/10-questions-for-gov-chris-christie-of-new-jersey/">interviewed Chris Christie</a> two weeks ago and asked him about potentially running in 2016. He said it would be &#8220;immature&#8221; for somebody to say at this point they were ready to run. Is that why you&#8217;re holding back? Would you rather make tax policy in Congress?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> I&#8217;d say premature, not actually immature. I have an important job to do here in Congress. I take this job very seriously. The people of Wisconsin elected me to do this job. So I&#8217;m doing my job. There is a right time and place to think about those things. That&#8217;s 2015. I&#8217;m going to keep my options open. I am on a track here in the House that I&#8217;m pleased with. I have chosen to forgo running for other things here in the House because I like where I am.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> You&#8217;re a football fan. There&#8217;s a bill in Congress to force the Redskins to change their name. Do you think they should have to?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">  I think that should be up to them. I think we should stay out of it. I haven&#8217;t given it any thought. We should focus on the problems facing this country that we have direct control over and let people in Washington and the team owners make that decision.</p>
	</div>
		<footer class="entry-footer">
